This is happening because casting from a subclass (List) to a extended class (RefInItemsListInput) is not allowed.
The interface is an extension of List. A solution is to:

1. Define the desired interface type as an extension of List&lt;Object&gt;
2. Create a class that implements the object
3. Create a new instance of the class from step 2 using the List inputs

In code this looks like this:
```
    public interface RefInItemsListInput extends List&lt;Object&gt; {
        class RefInItemsListInputImpl extends ArrayList&lt;Object&gt; implements RefInItemsListInput {
            public RefInItemsListInputImpl(List&lt;Object&gt; inst) {
                super(inst);
            }
        }
        static RefInItemsListInput of(List&lt;Object&gt; inst) {
            return new RefInItemsListInputImpl(inst);
        }
    }
```
And the test code is:
```
    @Test
    public void testPropertyNamedRefValidPasses() {
        // property named $ref valid
        RefInItems.RefInItems1.validate(
            RefInItems.RefInItemsListInput.of(
            Arrays.asList(
                MapMaker.makeMap(
                    new AbstractMap.SimpleEntry&lt;&gt;(
                        &quot;$ref&quot;,
                        &quot;a&quot;
                    )
                )
            )),
            configuration
        );
    }
```
Once can read all about it here and see some other solutions:
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/54370888/shortcut-for-parameterized-type

Remember that this`interface extends List&lt;object&gt;` solution will create an extra list, so it will use more memory than bare list types. If less space is needed, consider making the List&lt;Object&gt; type into a generic, and having a separate method that generates an instance of that generic.

