The core idea is to create a new array of the correct length (all values will be set to `0` by default), and then copy the content of the old array to the new array, but &quot;skip&quot; the first elements in the new array. We can achieve this with the following method:

    private static final int DIVISOR = 8;

    static byte[] pad(byte[] original) {
      int originalLength = original.length;
      if (originalLength % DIVISOR == 0) {
        return original;
      }
      int pad = DIVISOR - (originalLength % DIVISOR);
      byte[] result = new byte[pad + originalLength];
      System.arraycopy(original, 0, result, pad, originalLength);
      return result;
    }

[&lt;kbd&gt;`ideone.com` demo&lt;/kbd&gt;][ideone]

We &quot;skip&quot; the first elements of `result` by setting the 3rd parameter (`destPos`) of [`System::arraycopy` (`docs.oracle.com`)][systemArraycopyDoc] to `pad`.

[ideone]: https://ideone.com/Q4si6X

[systemArraycopyDoc]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/System.html#arraycopy(java.lang.Object,int,java.lang.Object,int,int)

&gt; _&quot;... What I want to do with this data is to pad left it so that it is of multiple of 8 bytes. ...&quot;_

Utilize the _[System#arraycopy](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/System.html#arraycopy(java.lang.Object,int,java.lang.Object,int,int))_ method.

Similarly, you can derive the next multiple of _8_, by using the _[Math#ceil](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Math.html#ceil(double))_ method.

Here is an example.

```java
byte[] pad(byte[] a) {
    int n = a.length, m = (int) (Math.ceil(n / 8.) * 8);
    byte[] temp = new byte[m];
    System.arraycopy(a, 0, temp, m - n, n);
    return temp;
}
```

And, here are some example usages.

```java
byte[] hello = { 0x68, 0x65, 0x6c, 0x6c, 0x6f };
hello = pad(hello);
out.println(Arrays.toString(hello));

byte[] helloworld = { 0x68, 0x65, 0x6c, 0x6c, 0x6f, 0x77, 0x6f, 0x72, 0x6c, 0x64 };
helloworld = pad(helloworld);
out.println(Arrays.toString(helloworld));
